V-Model (Verification and Validation Model)
Definition :

The V-Model (Verification and Validation Model) is an SDLC model in which every development phase has a corresponding testing phase. Testing activities are planned from the beginning, helping to detect defects early and improve software quality.

V-Model Phases:

Verification (Development Side):

Business Requirement Specification (BRS) – Defines business requirements.
System Requirement Specification (SRS) – Describes the system requirements.
High-Level Design (HLD) – Defines the overall system architecture and modules.
Low-Level Design (LLD) – Describes the detailed design of each module.
Coding – Developers implement the software.


Validation (Testing Side) :
Unit Testing – Tests individual modules.
Integration Testing – Tests interaction between modules.
System Testing – Tests the complete system.
Acceptance Testing – Verifies the software meets user requirements.
